The temperature dataset contains 21 columns from year 1996 to 2015 and 123 rows with daily temperature from July 1st to Oct 31st, cycling through every year. There are lots of noise (randomness) indicated by peaks and valleys, as you can see in the Excel plotted graph of the daily temperatures. We will analyze those randomness and smoothe out 'remove' some randomness using exponential smoothing.

Create data into time series

  1. First changing from dataframe/matrix set up to one long list of vectors using unlist.
temp_vec <- as.vector(unlist(temp[,2:21]))
#temp_vec
plot(temp_vec)

  1. Changing the long vectors just created to time series by starting at 1996 and repeating it every 123 observation until 2015
#?ts

temp_ts <- ts(temp_vec, start=1996, frequency=123) 
plot(temp_ts) 

Plotting the timeseries data, we realize that temp is fairy consistent in the range 70-90 with avg around 80. It has some level of seasonality with some seasonal peaks and valleys which do not look same overtime.

Now, viewing the components of the time series data separately to get a better understanding using ‘decompose’

#?decompose
plot(decompose(temp_ts)) 

Observed data lies on the top, so using moving average, the graph gives more information on trend, seasonality and noise. The seasonality looks very prominent and same, trend seems to be a mixture of upward and downward trends but does not show a clear pattern, while starting out at a lower trend, and the data shows randomness like any other dataset in the real world. 


Exponential smoothing will smooth out the time-series data allowing to put greater weight on recent observations and lesser weight on older observations. Choosing between additive or multiplicative depends on the situation where using multiplicative is recommended when the variation in seasonal or trend pattern also varies with the level of time-series (thus is proportional). Thus, if seasonal variation is consistent overtime, either additive or multiplicative will be fine. If variation increases overtime, multiplicative is useful. We will apply various exponential smoothers on the temperature timeseries data using HoltWinters function.

Breakdown into exponential smoothing - single (without any trend or seasonality), double and triple smoothing.

#1 single exponential smoothing WITH NO TREND nOR seasonality
#not including trend (beta) and seasonality (gamma) i.e., FALSE
#Leaving the alpha (level) and beta (trend) parameters as null allows the function to identify optimal parameters 

single_expo <- HoltWinters(temp_ts,beta=FALSE,gamma=FALSE)
single_expo

plot(single_expo)

So, the baseline estimate at the end is 63.30952, and the best value of alpha found is 0.8396301. [Of course, both of those have more significant digits reported than are reasonable.]

#Running CUSUM analysis, but on the seasonal factors.

# Running CUSUM model to detect change points in the time series data stored in the fit.df data frame

my_cusum <- function(Thresh=72, C=0) {
  changed <- c() # empty list will fill with change point indices
  year <- c()
  for (col in 2:20) { # iterates over columns 2 to 20 of the fit.df data frame.
    xt <- fit.df[, col]
    mu <- mean(xt)
    s1 <- fit.df[1, col]
    for (t in 2:length(xt)) {
      st <- max(0, s1 + (xt[t] - mu - C))
      s1 <- st
      if (st <= Thresh) {
        changed <- c(changed, temp[t, 1]) #add date to list
        year <- c(year, names(fit.df[col]))
        break
      }
      else {
      }
    }
  }
result <- data.frame(year=year, day=changed) #etected change points.
result
}
cs <- my_cusum(Thresh=70, C=2)
cs

#temp_m
Will focus on the results of the multiplicative model:
temp_m
#Smoothing parameters:
#alpha: 0.615003
#beta : 0
#gamma: 0.5495256

Smoothing parameters assign weights for historical and current data to consider. Based on the results of the multiplicative functin above, alpha 0.6 means that more recent data than historical used for level smoothing, beta 0 means that all historical data was used for trend smoothing, and gamma 0.54 means half recent and half historical data was used for seasonal smoothing. These smoothing parameters then generate coefficients used for forecasting purposes.

The seasonality in temperatures spiking up and down each consecutive year. Adding a blue line fitted to the time series data we can see no real trend in temperatures over time. It is pretty flat throughout with no significant movement up or down. The black lines is the observed one while the red one is the fitted line. Initially while the red and black lines don’t clearly overlap, over cycles the system adjusts itself from past learnings and it gets smoother into the black lines in next cycles

par(mfrow = c(1,1))
xhat=triple Exponential Smoothing output (which is aggregate of level, trend and seasonality). In the model, as date/time progresses, more data is fed into the model and fitted, so data changes and eventually stablilizes. In the graph above, level is fairly consistent, trend is not affecting at all, but seasonality is what's contrbuting to the noise in xhat (every time xhat went down, seasonality went down and xhat up/seasonality went up). The graphs for season has changed compared to the season graph in the decomposition (which was same period to period). It does not look consistent anymore and triggered later in the graph. These spikes and triggers could be investigated further by looking at the observed data points to understand if these are actual changes in seasonality or random noise.
